\section{Traffic Light Protocol}
\noindent Traffic Light Protocol (TLP) is a system of markings that designates the extent to which recipients may share potentially sensitive information.
\\\\
\noindent \textbf{Note:} TLP is not legally binding and does not override legal restrictions or obligations. TLP is not a formal classification scheme and was not designed to handle licensing terms, nor information handling or encryption rules.   TLP labels and their definitions are not intended to have any effect on freedom of information or “sunshine” laws or other laws in any jurisdiction, including the Cybersecurity Information Sharing Act of 2015, which provides certain protections for cyber threat indicators shared with federal agencies and also requires those agencies to share with one another.
\\\\
\noindent The purpose of TLP is “to facilitate greater sharing of potentially sensitive information and more effective collaboration.” Version 2.0 improves TLP by further clarifying sharing restrictions.
