\section{Introduction}

	\noindent Web application scanning (WAS) is the process of testing sites and applications hosted on the Internet for various known vulnerabilities and misconfigurations that could lead to unwanted information disclosure or other unintended consequences. Using an automated tool is one way to monitor and check for vulnerabilities and misconfigurations that can be exploited by a malicious actor. Other methods of discovering potential flaws, but not included in this assessment, include manually scanning each hosted service and looking for specific vulnerabilities one by one.


	\noindent Since the list of known vulnerabilities grows larger every day, it would be both time consuming and difficult to individually check for each vulnerability on your sites and applications.  Therefore, it is recommended that automated Web application scanning is performed on a regular basis to assist with the identification of potential issues that could arise and cause problems with a particular web application.


	\noindent The following report provides a snapshot as to what your web applications look like from an external perspective at the time of the scan. While reasonably thorough, we make no guarantee that all vulnerabilities and misconfigurations have been discovered.


	\noindent We hope that your organization can use this information to implement more effective security practices and better safeguard your web applications.

	\section{How to use this Report}


	\noindent As stated earlier, the intention of this report is to be a snapshot of the current state of your web applications as detected from an external scan. While Qualys offers some general suggestions based on the findings, the exact response to this information will vary based on the configuration of your overall system and the processes in place for change management. We encourage you to use this information to the best of your ability to meet your unique requirements, but we can offer a simple process to help you gain additional value from your report:
	\begin{enumerate}
		\item Look over the Executive Summary in the next section to get a general idea about what the results are looking like. If you have questions on any specific numbers, check the FAQ section, found in Appendix B. If the answer is not there, feel free to send an email to vulnerability@cisa.dhs.gov with your inquiry.
		\item Check out the detailed findings located in Attachment 1: Detailed findings in Appendix C: Attachments. This will give a comprehensive list of each finding, the URL(s) where the finding was discovered, and detailed information such as the payloads used to trigger the results, if applicable, and a detailed explanation of what each finding means and the potential
		\item Compare the sitemap in the "Sitemap" attachment in Appendix C: Attachments to what you currently believe is your overall catalog of Web Applications. This is a list of the links that were crawled in the "Discovery Scan" phase and might be able to tell you about resources or links that you thought were no longer accessible that can still be found.
		\item As you implement mitigations, subsequent scans can inform you as to whether the mitigations are successful or not.
	\end{enumerate}
